story:
Peacefully at her home, with her loving family by her side, on Tuesday 15th December 2020, Ann Bisset (nee Moir) aged 82 years. Beloved wife of the late Ian (Fraser) Corbett, a much loved and loving mam of Shirley and Kevin, a proud, loving and devoted grandma of Jasmin, Daniel, Jordan, Jade, James, Abbie-Jo, adored great-grandma of Esmé, dearly loved by Kevin's partner Sandra and her daughter Sarah Marie, amd the grand children's partners Jamie-Leigh, Megan, Scott, Lucas and Becky. Very sadly and sorely missed. 

Our family are so grateful for all your kind words and support in this difficult time.

story:
MacMillan are there for people in a very hard time, which so many of us will know firsthand.  They were there for my family.  But they only get to be there for us if we're all there for them, so I'm going to be doing 24 hours straight from 10am Sunday to finish out the year trying to get MacMillan the supply drop they need!

Join for the following possibilities:
-Weird Japanese games based on Jungian Psychology
-Interactive video game design
-Middle-of-the-night Phasmophobia
-My first time playing Among Us
-Genshin
-Conversations about tabletop gaming
-Stream Raiders to break apart the time

story:
We are creating a prize draw for a free full reflexology treatment. Prize draw will last from 22/12/2020 to 31/12/2020. 

All donations and fundraising support are very much appreciated!

Suggested donation is just £1 per entry, and each £1 donated by you counts as an entry.

(The names of each person who donates will be put into a hat and the person who wins the prize is randomly selected).

The prize winner can also choose to give the reflexology treatment as a gift.  

Macmillan Cancer Support helps everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can; physically, financially and emotionally. 

Donating through Just Giving is simple, fast and secure -with money sent directly MCS.

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support was there for my sister Angela in any possible way they could. 

I am wanting to and encouraging everyone to move as much as they can as a team to cover an accumulated distance of 6804 Km’s by April 29th. This distance is the walking distance from Lashkar Gah (Afghanistan) where she first fell ill to The Queen Elizabeth hospital (Birmingham) where they looked after her so amazingly. I will be using the hashtag #Move4Ange so I can keep on top of every single km people do. 

This challenge will start January 1st 2021 and until the 29th April 2021 the day she passed so peacefully.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
As many of you may know we sadly lost Kay on the 13th of  December after her battle with lung cancer. Two years ago Kay also suffered a heart attack which left her in hospital for 9 weeks but after defying many odds she came home fighting and returned to work at the bay tree. 

Due to corona virus we are only able to have a limited  number of people to attend Kay’s funeral. Her wish was for any donations to go to The British heart foundation so for this reason I am setting up this page so anyone that can not attend the funeral has the option to make a donation as a tribute to Kay. 

Kay was an amazingly strong lady and loved by many. It is a heartbreaking loss for all of her family and everyone that knew her so any donation made from the people that knew and loved Kay would be greatly appreciated as it can go towards our own donation to the foundation. 

Thank you for reading 






Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story: Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at GOSH. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support and everyone in Team GOSH taking on the iconic 2021 London Marathon will be helping to give seriously ill children the chance of a better future. For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Every day 619 children and young people arrive at GOSH to receive care and life saving treatments to ensure they can continue to lead healthy lives. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

story:
31 Miles.....Whilst Doing Dry January!!!

Which is worse????

So..... I wanted to do Dry January (without being pregnant)..... but with a Meaning, SO HERE IT IS!

What Better Reason or Charity than Great Ormond Street Hospital!!!
Who just happen to be doing their own January Challenge!
So here i am.... On The 22nd December 2020 feeling very optimistic that this is bloody marvellous idea! 
So I've Signed up!!!
31 Miles throughout January to add to my Dry January!
I am that sure that I will do it that I have added a forfeit!!
😱 If I fail... even by One Mile Or One Sneaky Drink.... I will also have to suffer a DRY FEBRUARY 😱
Wish me luck....
And feel free to sponsor my nightmare....(The Dry January more than The Running) 🤣

story:
Hello everyone!

It’s been a poo year and I’ve eaten too much. So this January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in ‘Running off Christmas’.

I'll be running 100 - yes ONE HUNDRED - miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH).

My younger brother Danny was a patient years back for tumour treatment and I remember how amazing they were.

I also know of my lovely friends who have had times there with their children. GOSH are amazing.

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

Any donation amount is sooooo appreciated. Thank you for your support.

Lots of love, Kirsty xx

story: Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at GOSH. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support and everyone in Team GOSH taking on the iconic 2021 London Marathon will be helping to give seriously ill children the chance of a better future. For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

story:

story:

Cancer has touched both our families lives and we would love your support in raising some much needed funds to help towards the find a cure.

Breast Cancer and Pancreatic Cancer are 2 areas where we would love to see our money contribute towards cures.

Thank you for your support.

Rowey and Simo

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

Appreciate this is a costly time for everyone, but my siblings and I would be obliged if you can, by any small way, acknowledge the magnificent work of the Marie Curie organisation who provide a much needed ‘end of life’ service to grieving families. We, my sister Trish, brothers Tommy, Kenny, Leslie and Danny,  have been recent recipients of the care and support offered by the Inverness district of the Marie Currie organisation, unfortunately for us, this has been twice over the last five months, firstly in July this year for the care of our beautiful mum Celia and in the past few weeks for our loving Dad Pat. We would be grateful if you could contribute, in some way, to this page please, like many other Charities, Marie Curie and and other voluntary organisations, despite being as much in demand, are struggling to survive during these difficult times due to fundraising opportunities being very much restricted. Therefore, we would be very thankful to you for any donation, large or small you wish to make to support this first class invaluable service. Thank You in advance!

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.name: WWF-UK
eventName: Chrimbo Limbo Yoga Workshop for WWF-UK
story:
Let's come together - online, of course - this Christmas and take some time out to move, rest and relax at the end of this turbulent year.

7pm, Tuesday 29 December 2020 (90min, on Zoom)

Thank you to all my students who have helped me support several charities already this year. Let's go out with a bang and do a little something to support WWF.

I have chosen WWF in memory of my friend Elliot Dallen who died in September. Some of you may have read his blog posts and/or articles in the Guardian about what he had learned about life during his illness. I met Elliot in Brazil in 2012, an area where there is mass deforestation and where WWF work. 

Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting https://wwf.org.uk

https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/sep/07/terminal-cancer-live-cancer-life-death
title: Dee's Chrimbo Limbo Yoga Workshop for WWF-UK

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
My Mum, Tina passed away suddenly and unexpectedly in June 2020 from an undiagnosed heart condition. Of the many things that she taught me, was an appreciation for and a desire to protect the environment we live in. 

While there are many worthy causes that could represent this ongoing passion for environmentalism, I have chosen WWF for their broad range of campaigns and global recognition. 

This has been the first year that she has not been with us to celebrate her birthday, and it will be the first Christmas without both my parents. In lieu of being able to give them a gift and a hug, I will be donating to a charity that I believe they would, in their memory. 

Please donate whatever you would like and, in doing so, remember my Mum, her passion for gardening, her love of the various animals that have been in her care, her commitment to studying for a Masters in Sustainable Agriculture alongside working full-time, and her tireless and selfless support and sacrifice for her family.

Thank you.
title: In memory of Tina Lyle

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
We at Wireless Federation, aim at fundraising for children in danger and supporting this particular cause, in collaboration with UNICEF. 

The outbreak of coronavirus brought suffering and misery for everybody across the globe and but has mostly affected those who are most vulnerable. Unicef is looking forward to generating funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by the pandemic especially in countries with weaker health systems.

Your small donation could provide enough for somebody who is in acute need of basic necessities like clothing, nutrition and safety from the disease. Together, we can not only help these vulnerable children but also the ones who've worked really hard to save our lives by risking theirs; health workers. 

Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members. Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to our page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

Stay home, stay safe and let's work for the betterment of the society, together.

Warm Regards,

Himanshu Johar
title: Wireless Federation's initiative to help children affected by Coronavirus

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
By the year 2040 there will not be enough water in the world to quench the thirst of the world population and keep the current energy and power solutions going if we continue doing what we are doing today. ... By 2050, 1 in 5 developing countries will face water shortages (UN's Food and Agriculture Organization).

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

I will be running in the 2021 Berlin Marathon to help raise money for the water shortage and growing global crisis. I know that times are challenging with the current COVID situation, but if you can donate any amount of money I would greatly appreciate it. Your donations will be going towards a great cause that can truly make a difference in the world. My goal is to raise $1250, but I am optimistic that we can reach a much higher number with your help. Thank you!
